                    </div>

                    <h2 style="font-size: 16pt; margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;">Array Mapping Mystery</h2>

                    <div style="font-size: 12pt;">
                        <p>In a complete binary tree, if a node is at index i (using 1-based indexing in an array), what is the index of its right child?</p>
                    </div>

                    
                    <div style="margin-top: 10px;">
                        <h3>Options:</h3>
                        <ul>
                            <li><p>2i − 1</p></li><li><p>i + 2</p></li><li><p>2i + 1</p></li><li><p>2i</p></li>
                        </ul>
                    </div><div style="margin-top: 10px; font-weight: bold; color: #15803d;">Correct Answer: <p>2i + 1</p></div>

                    <hr style="margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px; border: 0; border-top: 1px solid #ccc;" />
                </div>
            
                <div class="question-container">
                    <div class="header-badges">
                        <span>Q41</span>
                        <span class="complexity-Medium">Medium</span>
                        <span style="background-color: #eff6ff; color: #1d4ed8;">MCQ</span>
                    </div>

                    <h2 style="font-size: 16pt; margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;">Hidden Pointer Pathways</h2>

                    <div style="font-size: 12pt;">
                        <p>Which of the following is true about a threaded binary tree?</p>
                    </div>

                    
                    <div style="margin-top: 10px;">
                        <h3>Options:</h3>
                        <ul>
                            <li><p>It facilitates traversal without using a stack or recursion.</p></li><li><p>It must always be a balanced AVL tree.</p></li><li><p>It doubles the memory required for each node.</p></li><li><p>It&nbsp;always&nbsp;improves&nbsp;the&nbsp;search&nbsp;time&nbsp;complexity&nbsp;of&nbsp;a&nbsp;BST.​ </p><p></p><p></p><p></p></li>
                        </ul>
                    </div><div style="margin-top: 10px; font-weight: bold; color: #15803d;">Correct Answer: <p>It facilitates traversal without using a stack or recursion.</p></div>

                    <hr style="margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px; border: 0; border-top: 1px solid #ccc;" />
                </div>
            
                <div class="question-container">
                    <div class="header-badges">
                        <span>Q42</span>
                        <span class="complexity-Medium">Medium</span>
                        <span style="background-color: #eff6ff; color: #1d4ed8;">MCQ</span>
                    </div>

                    <h2 style="font-size: 16pt; margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;">Recursive Visit Pattern</h2>

                    <div style="font-size: 12pt;">
                        <p>What is the output of the following C++ snippet?</p><pre><code>void func(Node* r) {
  if(!r) return;
  func(r-&gt;left);
  cout &lt;&lt; r-&gt;data &lt;&lt; " ";
  func(r-&gt;right);
}</code></pre><p></p>
                    </div>

                    
                    <div style="margin-top: 10px;">
                        <h3>Options:</h3>
                        <ul>
                            <li><p>Post-order Traversal</p></li><li><p>Pre-order Traversal</p></li><li><p>In-order Traversal</p></li><li><p>Reverse In-order</p></li>
                        </ul>
                    </div><div style="margin-top: 10px; font-weight: bold; color: #15803d;">Correct Answer: <p>In-order Traversal</p></div>

                    <hr style="margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px; border: 0; border-top: 1px solid #ccc;" />
                </div>
            
                <div class="question-container">
                    <div class="header-badges">
                        <span>Q43</span>
