                    <h2 style="font-size: 16pt; margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;">Hashing</h2>

                    <div style="font-size: 12pt;">
                        <p>What does this C++ snippet calculate?</p><pre><code>int countProbes(int k, int table[], int m) {
    int i = 0;
    while(table[(k%m + i)%m] != -1 &amp;&amp; table[(k%m + i)%m] != k) 
        i++;
    return i + 1;
}</code></pre><p></p>
                    </div>

                    
                    <div style="margin-top: 10px;">
                        <h3>Options:</h3>
                        <ul>
                            <li><p>The total number of elements in the table</p></li><li><p>The index where k is stored</p></li><li><p>The value of the hash function</p></li><li><p>The number of probes to find k or an empty slot</p></li>
                        </ul>
                    </div><div style="margin-top: 10px; font-weight: bold; color: #15803d;">Correct Answer: <p>The number of probes to find k or an empty slot</p></div>

                    <hr style="margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px; border: 0; border-top: 1px solid #ccc;" />
                </div>
            
                <div class="question-container">
                    <div class="header-badges">
                        <span>Q62</span>
                        <span class="complexity-Medium">Medium</span>
                        <span style="background-color: #eff6ff; color: #1d4ed8;">MCQ</span>
                    </div>

                    <h2 style="font-size: 16pt; margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;">Hashing</h2>

                    <div style="font-size: 12pt;">
                        <p>What is the primary motivation for using a <strong>prime number</strong> for the table size m in Hashing?</p>
                    </div>

                    
                    <div style="margin-top: 10px;">
                        <h3>Options:</h3>
                        <ul>
                            <li><p>It is required by the C++ standard</p></li><li><p style="text-align: left;">Primes take up less memory</p></li><li><p>Primes make the modulo operation faster</p></li><li><p>To reduce collisions by ensuring better distribution</p></li>
                        </ul>
                    </div><div style="margin-top: 10px; font-weight: bold; color: #15803d;">Correct Answer: <p>To reduce collisions by ensuring better distribution</p></div>

                    <hr style="margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px; border: 0; border-top: 1px solid #ccc;" />
                </div>
            
                <div class="question-container">
                    <div class="header-badges">
                        <span>Q63</span>
                        <span class="complexity-Medium">Medium</span>
                        <span style="background-color: #eff6ff; color: #1d4ed8;">MCQ</span>
                    </div>

                    <h2 style="font-size: 16pt; margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;">Hashing</h2>

                    <div style="font-size: 12pt;">
                        <p>If m=11 and h(k)=k % m, for which k will Quadratic Probing i^2 and i Linear Probing produce the same first two probe indices (i=0, i=1)?</p>
                    </div>

                    
                    <div style="margin-top: 10px;">
                        <h3>Options:</h3>
                        <ul>
                            <li><p>Only for k = 0</p></li><li><p>Only for prime k</p></li><li><p>Never</p></li><li><p>For any value of k</p></li>
                        </ul>
                    </div><div style="margin-top: 10px; font-weight: bold; color: #15803d;">Correct Answer: <p>For any value of k</p></div>

